I need to find the number of red balls in the second urn.

**Setting up the problem:**

First urn: 8 red, 7 blue (total 15 balls)
Second urn: x red, 9 blue (total x + 9 balls)

**Calculating the probability of same color:**

The probability of getting two balls of the same color is the probability of:
- Both red OR both blue

P(both red) = P(red from urn 1) × P(red from urn 2)
$$P(\text{both red}) = \frac{8}{15} \times \frac{x}{x+9}$$

P(both blue) = P(blue from urn 1) × P(blue from urn 2)
$$P(\text{both blue}) = \frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{x+9}$$

**Setting up the equation:**

$$P(\text{same color}) = \frac{8}{15} \times \frac{x}{x+9} + \frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{x+9} = \frac{151}{300}$$

$$\frac{8x}{15(x+9)} + \frac{63}{15(x+9)} = \frac{151}{300}$$

$$\frac{8x + 63}{15(x+9)} = \frac{151}{300}$$

**Cross-multiplying:**

$$300(8x + 63) = 151 \times 15(x+9)$$

$$2400x + 18900 = 2265(x+9)$$

$$2400x + 18900 = 2265x + 20385$$

$$2400x - 2265x = 20385 - 18900$$

$$135x = 1485$$

$$x = \frac{1485}{135} = 11$$

**Verification:**

With x = 11:
- P(both red) = (8/15) × (11/20) = 88/300
- P(both blue) = (7/15) × (9/20) = 63/300
- P(same color) = 88/300 + 63/300 = 151/300 ✓

